  "sourceType": "CLASSIC",
  "sourceNotes": "Stout-and-chocolate as a baking combination appears in Irish and British food writing from the late twentieth century, often associated with St Patrick's Day baking. The combination works technically: the carbon dioxide in stout lightens the crumb, the malt sugars complement cocoa, and the bitter finish of a good stout balances the sweetness. The cream cheese frosting contrast is a later standard addition.",
